Hello, this is 6 Minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Neil.

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
And I'm Beth.

5
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:16.000
Lots of things can make us feel embarrassed.

6
00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.000
That self-conscious, uncomfortable feeling when your face blush is red

7
00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:23.000
and you wish you could just disappear.

8
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:26.000
Have you had any embarrassing moments, Neil?

9
00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:27.000
Yes, many.

10
00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:32.000
Once I met my parents in a car park and I saw them arriving in their car

11
00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:35.000
and I waved my hands around in a very silly way

12
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:39.000
but unfortunately I soon discovered that it wasn't my parents.

13
00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:41.000
It was another couple.

14
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:43.000
That's really embarrassing.

15
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:45.000
I remember answering the phone.

16
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:50.000
I thought it was my best friend and I said hello in a very silly voice

17
00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:52.000
and then they asked to speak to my dad.

18
00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:54.000
And it wasn't my friend.

19
00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:55.000
What was the voice?

20
00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:56.000
Hello.

21
00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:57.000
I do.

22
00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:01.000
But embarrassment is more than just shyness and blushing.

23
00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:05.000
When it comes to our health, there's no end of things to be embarrassed about.

24
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:10.000
Yes, and some people feel so embarrassed that they don't go to see a doctor

25
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:11.000
when they should.

26
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:14.000
Sometimes with serious consequences.

27
00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:18.000
In this program, we'll be discussing the issue of medical embarrassment.

28
00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.000
And as usual, we'll be learning some useful new words and phrases.

29
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:24.000
So, I have a question.

30
00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.000
Neil, according to the UK's nursing times newspaper,

31
00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:33.000
what percentage of people surveyed said they had delayed visiting their doctor

32
00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:38.000
out of embarrassment and then later being diagnosed with a health condition.

33
00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:45.000
Was it a 21%, b 41%, or c 61%.

34
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:47.000
So, I think it's probably a lot.

35
00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:49.000
So, c 61%.

36
00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:54.000
Okay, we will find out if that's correct at the end of the program.

37
00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:58.000
As humans, we get embarrassed if we feel different from others,

38
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:01.000
especially if the difference is physical.

39
00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:07.000
But how does feeling embarrassed about a medical condition impact our relationship with the doctor?

40
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:13.000
Here's Dr Vanessa Appier, consultant in sexual health at Bart's hospital in London,

41
00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:18.000
explaining more to BBC Radio 4 program inside health.

42
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:22.000
So, they'll delay accessing the clinic and also seeking treatment.

43
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:28.000
And so, then you'll often see people that could have been diagnosed with what's happening

44
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:34.000
much earlier and could have had earlier intervention, but it's delayed quite significantly.

45
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.000
And so, I then feel that we see a lot of people suffering in silence, really.

46
00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:41.000
Many people delay going to the doctor.

47
00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:45.000
They postpone going or put it off until a later time.

48
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:47.000
As a result, their problem isn't diagnosed.

49
00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:53.000
To diagnose means to identify a disease or health problem through medical examination.

50
00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:59.000
For some, feelings of embarrassment are so strong, they prefer to suffer in silence,

51
00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:02.000
to struggle with pain without seeking help.

52
00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:07.000
Rather than visit the doctor, but fortunately, there are things you can do to help.

53
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.000
Writing your problem down, going with the friend,

54
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:15.000
and visiting a doctor you trust are some ideas, doctor, appear recommends.

55
00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:20.000
There are ways that doctors can help as well as doctor Vanessa Appier explains here

56
00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:25.000
to James Gallagher, presenter of BBC Radio 4 program inside health.

57
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:29.000
Can you tell us what techniques you used to put people at ease?

58
00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:35.000
I am a brain transparency to the conversation in own it and say that I'm going to be asking

59
00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:39.000
you some quite personal questions and there may be also into examination.

60
00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:45.000
I want to assure you that this is confidential, that this is a safe non-judgmental space.

61
00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:52.000
So really, I often name the words to create that space as well.

62
00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.000
Also in my manner, I would hope and in my non-verbal cues.

63
00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:03.000
James asks what doctors can do to put people at ease to make them feel calm and relaxed.

64
00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:07.000
And doctor Appier describes her ideal conversation.

65
00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:12.000
It's a safe space, it's non-judgmental, and what is said is confidential.

66
00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:15.000
Capt. Private and not shared with anyone.

67
00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:19.000
As well as discussing embarrassing problems, sensitively,

68
00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:22.000
doctor Appier also uses non-verbal cues.

69
00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:27.000
The expression on her face, her hand movements, and the tone of her voice

70
00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:31.000
rather than words to communicate and relax at the patient.

71
00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:36.000
Embarrassment is normal, and with support, hopefully more of us will feel safe to visit

72
00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.000
the doctor despite it.

73
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:41.000
Okay, Beth isn't it time to reveal the answer to your question?

74
00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:47.000
It is. I asked you what percentage of people said they had delayed visiting the doctor

75
00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:53.000
because they were embarrassed, but then had later been diagnosed with a health condition.

76
00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:54.000
Do you remember what you said, Neil?

77
00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.000
Yes, I think I said, see 61%.

78
00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:04.000
I'm afraid that is not the correct answer. It was, in fact, a 21% or just over a fifth.

79
00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:12.000
Okay, let's recap the new vocabulary we've used, starting with delay to postpone or put off until a later time.

80
00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:20.000
To diagnose a disease or medical condition, means to identify it by recognizing the symptoms and examining the patient.

81
00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:27.000
If you suffer in silence, you endure and struggle with painful feelings without asking someone for help.

82
00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:32.000
The phrasal verb, put someone at ease, means to make someone feel calm and relaxed.

83
00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:40.000
The adjective confidential means kept private and secret and describes information which is not shared with anyone else.

84
00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:49.000
And finally, non-verbal cues are types of communication using facial expressions, hand gestures or tone of voice rather than speech

85
00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:59.000
to show your feelings. Once again, our six minutes are up, but why not build your vocabulary and listening skills even more with the quiz and worksheet related to this program?

86
